deck_excerpt: An Artmage list with a small Strikers Engine and an example Combo
deck_description:
Artmage with a small Strikers engine (Example combo below)

Artmage isn't a particularly strong deck, but I've recently come to love it.
While looking into Strikers as a secondary engine semi-jokingly, I've come to be positively surprised both in the fun and usefulness the Strikers engine actually provides here.
One thing I'd like to mention specifically is Sky Stiker Ace = Zero.
She's...nice? Like, when you're going into her she feels good and I do find myself enjoying her presence in the deck as a pop 1 + summon raye + roze which can then lead into another pop by using raye to link into azalea, however, the fact she forces you to deck Raye and Roze is a little questionable and if I were to actually bring this list to an important tournament, I'd probably cut Zero, Raye, Roze, and Azalea, and replace them with 2 Super Poly in Main and 2 generic fusion targets in Extra. 
Obviously this deck doesn't have any immensely powerful 1ccs, and the optimal combo in this deck is always shifting very fast depending on how many discards you have for your field spell, whether you searched Medius or drew him, what you draw off Finmel, etc.

Either way, I'll add a basic combo below to give a basic idea of how the endboards can look.

Combo (Endboard at bottom):

Requirements: Engage (or Hornet Drones) + Medius the Pure and 1 blank S/T to discard

- Activate Engage to search Hornet Drones

- Activate Hornet Drones to Summon a Token

- Link the token into Kagari

- Use Kagari's effect to re-add Hornet Drones

- Use Hornet Drones to summon a Token

- Link the Token and Kagari into Cross-Sheep

- Normal Summon Medius

- Use Medius' Effect to Special Summon Power Patron from Deck

- Use Patron's Effect to fuse with Medius into Diactorus (Important: Place Diactorus into a Zone that Cross-Sheep points to!)

- CL1 Power Patron Trigger Effect to Add Alteration CL2 Cross Sheep to Special Summon Medius

- Activate Alteration to Set the Field Spell

- Use the Field Spell to discard your blank S/T and add Graflare to your Hand

- Use Graflare's Effect to Summon him from hand and set Assault from your Deck

- Activate Assault to search Medius

- Summon Medius from your hand (the Field Spell allows you to Summon one "Medius The Pure" aside from your Normal Summon per turn)

- If you have another S/T: Discard it with your Field Spell to search Finmel and use her Effect to Summon her and Draw one card. She's a very strong negate and the draw one may be a discardable S/T. If you can't get her, proceed with the rest of the combo anyway. She's just a nice extra body I wanted to mention. Most of the time you can get her in some way.

- Now you can either use your Cross-Sheep and one of your Medius to go into Zilo, use both of your Medius to go into S:P, or use both of your Medius and Cross-Sheep to go into Accesscode Talker. I will assume Zilo for the Endboard Summary below.

 

ENDBOARD:
1x Field Spell (Grind Game Potential)

1x Zilo (3x Zone negates)

1x Graflare (1x S/T Pop)

1x Finmel (Not guaranteed, see combo - board negate and ATK halve)

1x Medius (Body, not much else lol)

2x remaining hand cards

You have 9 one card combos and 7 more 1.5 card combos as for the combos 

THE MOST IMPORTANT THING IS YOUR FIELD SPELL, but I don't play terraforming it makes you too droll and lockable, thats wy we play 3 from the feild spell, 3 fallen of tistina and 3 fallen of tistina. After you get to your field spell you want to sent to GY the best support Miasma Dragon Tistina, he is everything that tistina did not have before so he will summon itself and search you the Demigon from then you make xyz 10 probably Varudras the Final Bringer of End Times or Tistina, the Divinity that Defies Darkness, but you want Tistina the Divinity when you have flipped your oponent's monseters ore for the OTK if you can't end this turn just do not make him, but this is not all after summoning Demigod It searches you a spell and more often the Breath of the Tistina if your opponent has a faceup monster and you contorl LIGHT Tistina you can flip his monster facedown and search a card, then you can search for Tainted of the Tistina and use ure additional Normal Summon to summon it using your opponent's monster and thus making it level 10 that gives you one more level 10 on the field. If you already have the Crystal God Tistina you can somehow get Play of the Tistina and if you are going first you can possibly set it and on your opponent's turn to summon it while having Demigod and like that you can flip all his cards but this is to risky setup better play it on your turn and make Varudras. Finally if you are secoond and you feel it you should totaly do Liebe OTK just spam level 10 bodies inflict 2k with Gustav and attack for 6k with Liebe if you are sure it will go as planned, but ideally to feel the statisfaction of TISTINA you go second make Tistina, the Divinity that Defies Darkness using Tainted of the Tistina and Crystal God Tistina and swing for 4k twice because you detach Tainted for the effect of Divinity so it makes 2 attacks and ideally your opponent has no board left.

Also just to add that I love the fact Varudras i the Final Bringer of End Times it has some godlike status just like Tistina.

deck_name: Tournament Harpie Deck - WCQ Regional Rio sept 14th 2025
deck_description:
Deck piloted by me during Rio de Janeiro's WCQ Regional on september 14th 2025.

 

Scored 2 wins out of 7 matches; those were against one Blue-Eyes/Buster Blader and one Dogmatika/Shadoll Stun. Some misplays made me lose some 2 matches I could reasonable win (against yuumi/sky striker and morganite/vanity stun).

 

About the concept: Primite is by far the best engine to mix with Harpies. It avoid your dependancy on normal summon, has one-card combos, adds consistency etc. Lode's effect lets you keep XYZ Pet Dragon with his effects and materials. Unfortunely I didnt have the time to try a smaller number of cards (I was expecting 45/47), but the starting hand ratio is 1 or 2 bricks out of 15 hands, that speaks for itself.

Some regrets: 3 cards in my side were specific for Vanquish Soul, I never engaged any, it would have been better to use Scenario Rotation as side against Yummi. Money issues didnt allowed me to have: Purulia, a 3rd beryl, droplet. But I'm quite satisfied of what this deck could do considering the current meta.

Needs some work, namely more dragons in the main

The goal of the deck is to consistently loop 3-4 times and end on Draco Future. Kanzashi is critical for the 4th and 5th loop to save your M7s. Hearld does the same when you start on Grimness as your normal. You have 15 points to do whatever you want in your side deck. There is an arguement for dropping 1 Prep and then maindecking a Called by. 

 

Been test handing this since the format announcement and it's almost always going to rip 2 cards and end on Draco (2 when you rip 4 cards). Past that will take time and practice. 4 card rips are more consistent now but you have to be thinking very far ahead.

deck_name: So you want to play Paleozoics?
deck_excerpt: 98 point 60 card Paleozoic Labrynth pile for casual Genesys format
deck_description:
This will be written with the perspective of a new player in mind, as Genesys format is designed to bring in returning players to a less complicated format.
Welcome, so you want to play Paleozoics? Paleozoic is a slow control deck that has so many tools in its toolbox between the main deck and extra deck that it can deal with almost any situation. The gameplan here is to grind your opponent out of resources with your powerful trap effects and almost endless recycling. There are no “one card combos" and every hand you draw will have a varied path towards victory. If this sounds like something you are interested in then read on as I will detail every card as well as give a short explanation and gameplay example that you can use to begin mastering this deck.

The Labrynth Package
A lineup of Lady, Arias, and Arianna. These cards are here to support a Paleozoic gameplan not a Labrynth gameplan, which is why there is no Lovely, Welcome/Big Welcome, or furniture.
While Arias is in the graveyard you are able to use it to discourage your opponent from doing something called chain blocking. This is a game mechanic in which your opponent responds to one of your trap effects in order to "block" your Paleozoics from "seeing" it, as every Paleozoic says "when" which means they must be activated directly after the activation of a trap.
Arianna is a simple searcher to add a Labrynth name that you might be missing, Archfiend will be able to add Mirror Force, and Lady is able to add anything that your heart could desire.

The Paleozoic Names
Canadia can flip your opponent's monster face down, keep in mind if your opponent is on an XYZ or Synchro deck that this will stop them from being able to use that monster as material.
Dinomischus is an excellent piece of removal that is hard for a lot of decks to deal with, and it also allows you to fill up your graveyard.
Marrella is so versatile because it can send anything you need to the graveyard that it is hard to give advice for, however some notable cards that you will want to make sure you have are Transaction Rollback and Rise to Full Height.
Olenoides main purpose is being able to recycle your Transaction Rollbacks after they have been used and your Paleozoics if they end up banished. Keep in mind that it returns any banished card, even cards that have been banished face down by something like a Kashtira Fenrir.
Anomalocaris the “boss monster” of Paleozoics, it generates you advantage as well as disrupting your opponent. However due to the slower nature of this deck you don’t want to rush this card out as soon as possible. Wait until you have summoned an Opabinia and filled up your graveyard.
Opabinia is the easily accessible searcher for this deck, you are able to access any trap through adding a Marrella with this effect. Keep in mind that Opabinia is immune to monster effects, so if you opponent wants to stop your plays with an Effect Veiler or an Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring you can sleep soundly knowing they discarded a card for no reason.

Transaction Rollback
The most flexible and valuable card in this deck, it can be anything and it can even ignore one per turn clauses on cards. Get this card into the graveyard as soon as possible and by any means possible.
The simplest way is by using any two Paleozoics to make Paleozoic Opabinia, allowing you to add Paleozoic Marrella and then immediately activate to send Transaction Rollback directly to the graveyard.

Magicolloidal Sol
This can make anything in the extra deck, which has been designed as a toolbox, but the two Paleozoic XYZ should be prioritized if possible.
However if you need to negate something you can make Toadally Awesome, or if you need removal to protect your life total you can make Merry Melffys or Sky Cavalry Centaurea.

Mirage of Nightmare
Before discarding your hand keep in mind that Paleozoic Opabinia allows you to activate Paleozoics from your hand.
If it is difficult to manage discarding your entire hand every turn, I recommend replacing it with Needlebug Nest in the side deck.

Traptantalizing Tune
Better than Pot of Greed in this deck as this will allow you to fill up your graveyard with Paleozoics as well as recycle a spent Transaction Rollback.

Balance of Judgment
Our draw trap of choice for the ability to copy it in the graveyard with Transaction Rollback while you have an empty field to fill up your entire hand. If you are finding yourself unable to maneuver through situations in which it would be beneficial, I recommend replacing it with Accumulated Fortune or Hope for Escape in the side deck.

Destructive Daruma Karma Cannon
This is one of the best playmakers the deck has to offer, it does so much heavy lifting for being such a simple effect.
If you flip a Paleozoic that has been summoned from the graveyard face down with it, it will be counted as a "new card" and will not be banished if it leaves the field.
It can remove any unaffected boss monsters as the text says that your opponent must send the card their control to the graveyard, not this trap's effect.
This is the main trap that you will want to be looping with Transaction Rollback.

Elemental Burst
You might be asking yourself how you are going to tribute a wind, water, fire, and earth monster to activate this card, well if this card and Transaction Rollback are both in the graveyard, you can activate Transaction Rollback to copy Elemental Burst without having to pay the cost.
This card is very bad to draw and you should prioritize discarding it with Paleozoic Dinomischus and Traptantalizing Tune, sending it directly to the graveyard with Paleozoic Marrella, or destroying it with Trap Holic.

Fiend Griefing
The graveyard has the nickname of "the second hand" for how many different decks abuse it, so being able to disrupt your opponent while also generating advantage for yourself by sending either Arias or Absolute King Back Jack makes this a very powerful card in this deck.

Lost Wind
A discount Infinite Impermanence, this card will only be able to affect special summoned monsters, however the monster you negate will remain that way forever, there is no "end of turn" clause here.
It can also be reused from the graveyard and recycled from banishment by Traptantalizing Tune and Paleozoic Leanchoilia.

Mirror Force
Backrow removal comes with a heavy point cost associated with it and it remains to be seen if people are willing to pay that cost, if not it will be tricky to remove the Mirror Force even if they know you have set it with Labrynth Archfiend.
If you are playing against a deck with monsters that can not be destroyed by card effects or a deck that has a lot of backrow, I recommend replacing this with Heavy Storm Duster in the side deck.

Rise to Full Height
This card is very hard to grasp in a vacuum however if you play with the deck for a while you will begin to understand the utility of it. You are able to just activate it whenever you want on your own turn if you need to summon a Paleozoic to make a play, and you are able to protect one of your monsters by giving it a massive defense buff.
A useful tip to keep in mind is that if you have two of these cards in your graveyard, and you activate both of them with each targeting a different monster, your opponent will be unable to attack you at all as there is no legal attack target.

Trap Holic and Trap Trick
These are very flexible searchers in this deck and you will be able to ignore both of their restrictions very easily.
Trap Holic does not negate your own card so you can destroy one of your own traps and still gain the effect.
And if you use Transaction Rollback to copy Trap Trick you will not be restricted to using only one more trap effect as Trap Trick says "after this card resolves" and you did not resolve Trap Trick, you resolved Transaction Rollback.
However if you are activating Trap Trick itself, keep the restriction in mind.

Waboku
While the card is designed to protect you and your Paleozoics from battle you are actually able to activate it on your own turn to potentially summon a Paleozoic from the graveyard allowing you to make an XYZ. For this reason Waboku is played over a card like Threatening Roar.

Absolute King Back Jack
A fiend that you can use to generate advantage by sending it to the graveyard with Fiend Griefing if you already have an Arias in rotation.
If Labrynth Archfiend is not working for you then you can replace it with this card.

Mischief of the Gnomes
An absolutely devastating card that has always seen some niche play, with the function of XYZ and Synchro monsters requiring specific levels of monsters to be summoned you will be able to completely shut down any non-Fusion deck with this card.
This card is extremely matchup dependent so advice is hard to give, however some suggestions on what to replace are Balance of Judgement, Mirror Force, Fiending Griefing, or Lost Wind. Just try to keep in mind which of these would not be useful in your matchup.

Extra Deck
The extra deck was designed to be as simple to understand with no crazy combos.
Merry Melffys, Sky Cavalry Centaurea, Onibimaru Soul Sweeper, and The Phantom Knights of Cursed Javelin are all different forms of removal that you can use to deal with as many potential threats your opponent can make.

Toadally Awesome, Utopic Future, and Utopic Draco Future are negates that also gain you advantage by stealing your opponents cards.

Ninja Shadow Mosquito allows you to deal a lot of damage and punish your opponent for summoning a high attack point monster.

Mannequin Cat won’t come up in every duel however when it does it can be a very easy way for you to summon a Labrynth monster from your deck.

 

Good luck :3

deck_excerpt: Last Turn is legal for some reason so I wanted to try something.
deck_description:
I have no idea if this is actually good but I wanted to see if I could make a Last Turn deck in this format because why is it legal and not 100 points.

The idea is that you can get your LP low with the Dinomorphia cards to be able to activate Last Turn (which you can search with Trap Tracks, Trap Holic and Arias), and make your one monster be a beefed up Kentregina. And if their one main deck monster is able to destroy Kentregina, then she can float into one of the guys from grave so you can at least draw.

And then if the Last Turn part of the deck doesn't work out, you at least have some amount of a backup plan in Rexterm-less Dinomorphia.

Not sure if there's a better use of the remaining 22 points (cuz there's no reason not to use the 3 Impact) than playing 3 Judgement, and I don't know if the side deck is any good, but this is mostly just, like, a starting point pffffffft

deck_excerpt: A test version of the new Genesys Format
deck_description: A test version of the new Genesys Format
Early look into the Goblin biker PUNK potential. GP engine can be cut or reduced for other interactions

This is a deck built around the stat+spellcaster-based synergy of the Charmer support, primarily it's newer traps and spells. Charmers as an archetype were unfortunately never conceived to be played together, so when Konami gave them a structure deck by popular demand, a generic solution to bind lots of archetypes into a pile that works somewhat with charmers as the glue inbetween them was what they came up with. We will soon be getting the chronicles deck with 2 additional pieces of support plus possible promo's from the anime shorts, so I thought to introduce the deck to those who might become interested in how it works and who did not want to play stun based on that. 

As a foreword, the deck has no in-house resource game as of yet and many of your interruptions are once only, unless you recover them. The most effective resource game we have currently is looping Witch of the Black Forest by various means (equipping to zoroa or to the allure queens, resummoning with selene). Other than that, you could run a 1-of pot of avarice that you can search of Thrust and have it whiff after DD Crow gets chained. The new support we are getting will have quite some weight it needs to pull, but I will not abandon my pet deck.

 

The key idea is to resolve Awakening of the Possessed - Nefariouser Archfiend, which can summon itself from the deck without starting a chain by sending a spellcaster and an Lv4 or lower earth from the field to the graveyard. On summon, he will revive a monster from your grave and after linking these two off again, he will search one of the charmers' backrow. Typically you'll want to fetch Possessed Partnerships   This card lets you summon a Spellcaster with 1500DEF from hand or grave without targeting, then if you control 2+ attributes, you can destroy a card without targeting. Thanks to several monsters with triggers or quick effects, this interruption often sets up additional interruptions. If summoning Gravekeeper's Shaman, it can also serve to interrupt grave effects, as Shaman's effect is continuous. If you do not have a 1500DEF spellcaster or a way to access one before your opponent's turn, you can instead search Unpossessed. We run this card to help rebuild a broken board/gain additional pieces, but it is a much more reactive card, dependent on the opponnent. Typically, we only trigger this card ourselves during the opponent's end phase, if the opponent has himself not destroyed any of our monsters, by destroying one of our own with the graveyard effect of Nefarious Archfiend Eater of Nefariousness to then summon itself. Due to this card being slow, it is not always played.

 

Witch of the Black Forest, Spoon, the Seal of Magistus [to be renamed Spenta] and Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame are your 1-card-combo's, though the deck is not built to be a big combo deck, it is very much mid-range and will run out of steam if thought of as a combo deck. Pace yourself. Witch can be linked off for Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden and then search Nefarious Archfiend Eater of Nefariousness, which special summons itself if you control a spellcaster. A Witch gets you to at least Silhouhatte+Azurune+Partnerships, but of course you can push further than that if you summon Endymion, the Crescent of Magistus. Other than that, there are of course 2-card-combo's. If you already opened Nefarious, it is advised to search based on matchup. Droll, Nibiru, Shaman, Ecclesia and Cartesia are your typical searches if you did not yet have access to any of them. Since you have little recursion, you will want to close out games fast. For that reason there's a selene+accesscode package, though as mentioned before, Selene can be used to loop witch as well if that is preferable. A point to be noted:Kurikara Divincarnate does not activate in order to gain attack, so she can be summoned as a big body the same turn she is added off WotBF's effect. This in combination with Accesscode Talker is your most secure way of closing out the later games of the match.

 

There are more variants to the charmer deck, such as a Saggi The Dark Clown pile which I will now be re-exploring with Genesys format in mind. If you have bcome interested, check out the Archetype Discord repository to find the charmer server. If you google it, you will find a reddit (ugh) post that links to it.

deck_excerpt: An experimantel build of Runick paleo for the Genesys format
Genesys format FTK deck focused on consistency.
deck_description:
Reversal Quiz FTK is a combo strategy that utilizes a deck full of spells and deck-thinning cards to try and kill the opponent in one turn (preferably the first turn, before the opponent even has a chance to play a card of their own).

The deck uses a combination of Pot of Greed and draw spells, as well as deck-thinning cards like Thunder Dragon and Toon Table of Contents to increase the density of draw cards left in the deck. Regulus the Fairy Beast is the rank 4 engine of choice here, as it can put a Field Spell back into the deck to draw one card deeper when activating Daigusto Emeral or Dugares. You also need to run at least one card that either halves your LP or a card that pays somewhere between 500 and 900 LP. Extra-Foolish Burial ends up giving you an extra draw, which is why it's used here, but there are other options.

Once the player’s lifepoints are 500 or less, the combo is finished by equipping Black Pendant to your XYZ monster and activating Reversal Quiz. At the time Reversal Quiz is activated, there will be only Spell Cards in the deck, so it's guaranteed to hit. The opponent will now have 500 or less life points. Black Pendant, which was sent to the graveyard during the resolution of Reversal Quiz, will trigger in a new chain to deal the remaining damage and end the game. A Feather of the Phoenix can be used to place a Spell Card on top of the deck, in case either Black Pendant or Reversal Quiz are in the bottom of the deck.

Side deck choices should be focused on stopping Droll & Lock Bird and Hanewatta, which are likely the most common counters to this strategy. A well-timed D.D. Crow can hurt as well. You should always side out the Regulus engine when siding in Amano-Iwato.

The only cards you'll realistically use in your Extra Deck are Dugares, Daigusto Emeral, and Gagura. You can fill in the remaining slots with whatever you want. The whole deck is 95 Genesys points (30 each for the Pots, 1 each for the Into the Voids, 1 for Emeral, and 1 for the Zexal spell). So there's some space left to customize and adjust it if needed. A 2-card rank 3 engine that doesn't use the Normal Summon (Magnifistorming?) may be used to draw an additional card with XYZ Armor Torpedo.

deck_excerpt: Blue eyes Primite Kaibaman Genesys Blue-Eyes sage
deck_description: Kaibaman Primite Blue Eyes deck for genesys format

Umi Guide

I've been playing this deck for the last few years, and day by day, I'm trying to make it more consistent and solid. It's not based on a main strategy — it's more of a "do your best with what you have" kind of deck. So it’s really about knowing the deck deeply and thinking carefully about your options. That’s why I love it.

We’re a go-first deck. Our main control monsters are, of course, Electric Jellyfish and Ocean Dragon Lord – Kairyu-Shin, used to control the field and block your opponent’s summons. If you have both in hand, you usually go for Jellyfish to send A Legendary Ocean to the GY, and then summon Kairyu-Shin. From here, you have several options depending on your hand and your strategy. You should activate Kairyu-Shin’s effect and choose between:

- Another A Legendary Ocean (not ideal, in my opinion)

- Sea Stealth II, which gives you "Umi with steroids"

- Sea Stealth Attack (my favorite option), which lets you bring back the A Legendary Ocean you sent to the GY earlier without wasting resources, and gives you two bonus effects — saving one of your monsters and offering removal during the Battle Phase. It's also a great surprise for your opponent, who might see their board vanish after setting it up.

- Kairyu-Shin’s Dark Reef — only go for this if you potentially have more than one "Umi" on the field or if you already have Sea Stealth Attack. If you activate both in a chain (preferably Dark Reef first), you can send A Legendary Ocean to the GY and recover it with Sea Stealth Attack.

Abyss Shark is another key monster in the deck because it allows us to search for other sharks. Again, your choice depends on the situation. The two best targets are N.As.H. Knight and Number 4: Stealth Kragen. Both Crystal Shark and Dream Shark are good for this, but be very careful:

With Crystal Shark, you can go for either Rank 5 (N.As.H.) or Rank 4 (Kragen) since Crystal and Abyss give you flexibility. However, Crystal locks you into only Xyz Summons for the rest of the turn.

Dream Shark can only go for Rank 5 (or Rank 4 if you have A Legendary Ocean on the field). So plan accordingly before choosing which shark to play.

Final tip on sharks: Crystal Shark is a great option if you already have Number 4: Stealth Kragen on the field, since you can halve an opponent’s monster’s ATK and then summon Crystal Shark for free. 

Icejade Ran Aegirine is a good shortcut to Synchro Summons. Like Dream Shark, keep A Legendary Ocean in mind and decide beforehand whether you want to go for a Level 10 or Level 8 Synchro. Crystal Shark is also a solid option here since its GY revival effect can come in handy.

Lappis Dragon... my dear friend. I think I’m the only person in the world who plays this guy in their deck. This bro has given me the greatest joys — and the biggest headaches. It can be a game-changer or the reason for your defeat. But seriously, it’s surprisingly useful thanks to its ability to be summoned when added to your hand — whether from the deck or GY. This works especially well with Ice Barrier, which adds monsters from the GY, giving you a surprise 2600 (potentially 2800) ATK body during the Battle Phase.

Fish Sonar is basically your searcher for Electric Jellyfish or Kairyu-Shin.

Sea Stealth II is especially useful with Sea Stealth Attack — you can "revive" a monster from the GY or special summon one at the End Phase. You summon a monster from your hand or GY using Sea Stealth II, then banish it with Sea Stealth Attack to bring it back at the End Phase.

The Extra Deck is quite simple and straightforward. There's not much to explain — the monsters do different things, and sometimes it’s not even worth going into them. Remember, this is a control deck, so you won’t be doing long combos. Often it’s not necessary, since Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin can handle things on his own — especially in today's Yu-Gi-Oh!, where WATER monsters are barely in the meta, so no one can summon anything under his floodgate.

Hope this guide helps you get more comfortable playing the deck! Feel free to ask for help or leave suggestions in the comments!

deck_excerpt: Claim victory with the sacred flames!
deck_description:
A Flame Swordsman engine adds extra fire monsters and explosive interactions to this Fire King deck, providing both a strong board presence and additional resilience to board breakers.

On the Flame Swordsman Engine

Your primary playstarter for the Flame Swordsman engine is the Fighting Flame Swordsman, who can search for a spell or trap that mentions the Flame Swordsman if he's normal or special summoned. You can special summon the Fighting Flame Swordsman from your deck by destroying the Mirage Swordsman with a card effect. Your main search target with the Fighting Flame Swordsman's effect is the Flame Swordsrealm, which lets you send the Fighting Flame Swordsman from your field to the graveyard to fusion summon the Ultimate Flame Swordsman. The Ultimate Flame Swordsman is a powerful boss monster that can target and destroy 1 monster your opponent controls while dealing 500 burn damage. If he's equipped with an equip spell, this effect becomes a quick effect.

Fighting Flame Dragon is the card you'll equip to the Ultimate Flame Swordsman. Its quick effect allows it to equip itself from your field or your graveyard to the Ultimate Flame Swordsman as an equip spell, granting him +700 attack and the ability to attack twice per turn. You can send the Fighting Flame Dragon from your extra deck to your graveyard via Fighting Flame Swordsman's graveyard effect.

The Ideal Flame Swordsman Fire King Combo

Requires Fire King Courtier Ulcanix + Mirage Swordsman

1. Normal summon Ulcanix.

2. Activate Ulcanix's effect to destroy the Mirage Swordsman and search for Legendary Fire King Ponix.

3. Chain link 1: The Mirage Swordsman's effect activates to special summon Fighting Flame Swordsman from your deck.

Chain link 2: Special summon Ponix from your hand with his effect.

4. Chain link 1: Ponix searches for Fire King Sanctuary.

Chain link 2: Fighting Flame Swordsman searches for Flame Swordsrealm. Always activate Ponix as chain link 1 here, to protect it from disruption. Your Fire King plays are the core of this deck.

5. Activate Fire King Sanctuary and set Fire King Island face-up in your field spell zone.

6. Activate Fire King Island's effect to destroy Ulcanix and search for Sacred Fire King Garunix.

7. Chain link 1: Activate Ulcanix's effect to special summon Fire King High Avatar Garunix from your deck.

Chain link 2: Activate Sacred Fire King Garunix's effect to special summon himself from your hand.

Like Ponix, this chain protects Ulcanix from disruption.

8. Activate Sacred Fire King Garunix's effect to destroy Fire King Avatar Barong, setting up your future plays.

9. Activate Flame Swordsrealm.

10. Use the Flame Swordsrealm's effect to send the Fighting Flame Swordsman to the graveyard to fusion summon the Ultimate Flame Swordsman.

11. Activate the Fighting Flame Swordsman's graveyard effect to send the Fighting Flame Dragon from your extra deck to your graveyard.

12. Activate Fighting Flame Dragon's graveyard effect to equip it to the Ultimate Flame Swordsman.

Your board now consists of Ponix, Sacred Fire King Garunix, High Avatar Garunix, Fire King Sanctuary, Fire King Island, Flame Swordsrealm, and the Ultimate Flame Swordsman equipped with Fighting Flame Dragon. In your graveyard lies the Mirage Swordsman and a destroyed Barong.

Ponix is there for emotional support.

The Ultimate Flame Swordsman is primed for targeted monster destruction on your opponent's turn.

You can summon a rank 8 xyz by using the Sacred Fire King Garunix and High Avatar Garunix on your field, or you wait until the opponent's turn to xyz summon Garunix Eternity, Hyang of the Fire Kings with Fire King Samctuary's effect. Garunix Eternity's effect can nuke the board if he's xyz summoned.

Barong in your graveyard can search Fire King High Avatar Kirin during your opponent's standby phase. High Avatar Kirin can destroy 1 of your Fire King monsters during your opponent's main phase, triggering your other Fire King monsters' or Mirage Swordsman's effects. The Mirage Swordsman can special summon himself from your graveyard if any of your fire fusion monsters, like the Ultimate Flame Swordsman, are destroyed by battle or card effect.

Playing Around Nibiru

Nibiru, the Primal Being is the bane of this deck, but a slight modification to the Ideal Combo can mitigate its impact. At step 6, you can destroy Ponix instead of Ulcanix, then proceed to step 7 without summoning High Avatar Garunix from your deck. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, Ponix returns to your hand, and Barong searches for High Avatar Kirin. High Avatar Kirin can destroy Ponix during your opponent's main phase, triggering Sacred Fire King Garunix's graveyard effect and helping you recover your board.

Some Tips

Fighting Flame Swordsman can search for the Mirage Swordsman.

The Mirage Swordsman can special summon the original Flame Swordsman or any level 7 lower monster that mentions the Flame Swordsman from your deck or extra deck. The original Flame Swordsman is the best target because you can equip it with the Fighting Flame Dragon.

You can special summon Fighting Flame Dragon with the Flame Swordsdance's first effect, then special summon the Ultimate Flame Swordsman with the Flame Swordsdance's second effect. This provides an extra interaction on your opponent's turn.

deck_excerpt: I feel like Konami should hit some of the Ryzeals to more than just 20 points lmao
deck_description:
Rank 4 spam deck that invests most of its points into a couple of Ryzeal cards and a copy of Onomatopaira. 3x Onomatopickup makes Paira far more accessible, which is crucial for searching a ton of extension, but keep in mind that it is susceptible to pop effects when going second. The Ryzeal engine does not need to be opened, rather you just make Duo Drive with your first 2 level 4s, search Sword and Cross, special Sword, search Star Ryzeal (which is free). Then with another extender in hand (which this deck's consistency will pretty much guarantee you'll have), you make an Xyz such as Gagagaga Girl (if comboing without Paira, as this list doesn't run Full Armored Xyz, but you can choose to search it if you have a target you like to make with it!) or an endboard piece like Starliege Photon Blast Dragon to insulate your board from popular blowouts like Raigeki or Dark Hole (good luck dealing with DRNM though). After that, you may then special Star by detaching the now-available material in order to set Plasma Hole and make Detonator, for a Cross negate + 4 total pops (or 5 if you choose to keep the dead Duo Drive on board).

If you open Ascended Sage or Seventh Ascendance, however, you have the former as a free body searchable off Tachyon (making it best to use Ascendance to grab Tachyon first, then reveal Star Cestus off Tachyon to search the Warrior-type Ascended Sage), which can then Xyz off with another body for any Rank 4 Utopia you want to use (I use Utopia Rising due to its utility effect if applicable) to search Rank-Up-Magic Zexal Force (1 point), which will never be unable to activate due to being able to place another ZS - Ascended Sage onto the top of the deck. You then Rank Up your Utopia into Ultimate Leo Utopia Ray, which then detaches to equip Twin Pegasus Spear from deck for its unique non-activated negation, before continuing with your combo with your remaining resources in hand. Going second, or on Turn 3 after fending off your opponent's efforts, you can equip Dragonic Halberd from the Extra Deck to skyrocket Leo's attack to push for game, with Halberd getting to special itself to then attack with another 3k body after Leo's attack.

Dodododo Warrior is an important 1-card combo enabler to talk about. Its effect when detached lets you search a Zubaba from deck, which will be Utopic Onomatopoeia for its utility in getting brickier things out of hand for extension, i.e. a second Dodododwarf Gogogoglove stuck in hand, or a Zubaba Ganbara Knight if you made Gagagaga Girl too early (which is the only reveal target for its own effect in this list). However, this effect cannot be activated when detached for Ryzeal Duo Drive, as its search effect does not detach for cost, thus making the detach part of the effect rather than a detach to activate the effect.

In terms of other additions:

  • Eclipse Twins is in here like with pretty much every top Ryzeal list in the past, being able to use a dead Duo Drive as material while clearing more board space for further extension (a problem the deck runs into a bit without the ability to special any Xyz monsters to the EMZ in this format), as well as being strong for damage pushes.
  • Dark Hole is mainly maindecked at 2 copies due to making better use of my spare 6 points than running 1 copy of Shifter, though this deck can play alright under Shifter as well. This slot is flexible if you want something else, but considering the necessity of using the other 94 points, having this solid board breaker at 2 copies is probably one of the best deckbuilding options you can do here. DRNM is also in the side deck to make board-breaking even easier, especially in tandem with Hole to shutdown any other decks running destruction protection, like other Rank 4 spam strategies (Starliege Photon Blast Dragon) or Dragon Rulers (Ruddy Rose Dragon).
  • 2 copies of Sakitama are ran, albeit without Aratama. While Aratama can search it for the same amount of combo impact as Gogogo Goblindbergh, Seventh Tachyon can also search it through revealing Star Seraph Sentry, and it doesn't need to be searched off Aratama's normal summon for it to be a free body.
  • Plugin is ran as a 1-of since it can be searched off of Star Ryzeal or Duo Drive as an alternative if you open one of the normal search targets. It also can extend by reviving an Xyz to make Eclipse Twins later on.

Gimmick Puppet doesn't actually lose out from much due to the Genesys points system. Sure, it loses Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls, which is 100 points because making all of your Gimmick Puppets unaffected by non-Xyz Monster effects is kind of broken in a format with only Rituals, Fusions, Synchros, and Xyz Monsters, but on the bright side, you can still play the Deck as a nice little control Deck centered around CXyz Gimmick Puppet Fanatix Machinix and the Puppet Traps (Puppet Shark and Service Puppet Play). 

Kochobo's Hinamatsuri is a very nice free extender for Machine Xyz Decks. And definitely don't forget about Puppet Shark. It detaches 1 from an Xyz to excavate the top 4 cards of your Deck, and you get to choose 1 of them. If it is a Monster or Spell, you get to add it to your hand. If it is a Trap, you can set it and it can be activated this turn. So, either you just add a handtrap to hand or set Solemn Strike. Also, I tossed in Phantom Knights' Rank-Up-Magic Force to give the Deck access to Raidraptor - Rising Rebellion Falcon and Raidraptor - Ultimate Falcon on subsequent turns to help close out the game a little more quickly. 

Only thing about the Deck is that I am not too sure about its capability of going into backrow Decks. There are 3 copies of Cosmic Cyclone in the Side Deck and Twin Twister is also 0 points, but Gimmick Puppet is just naturally a Deck that is better at dealing with monsters rather than Spell/Traps. I guess you could swap some cards around to get enough points for a playset of Evenly Matched to keep in the Side Deck, but at least backrow Decks in Genesys are probably like setting Normal Traps instead of floodgates which is much nicer for the mind. 

Side Deck has Lava Golem because with Gimmick Puppet Rouge Doll, you don't have to commit to a Normal Summon for your plays, especially since the only Normal Summon in the Deck is Gimmick Puppet Little Soldiers. I guess you could play The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode if you wanted to instead of Lava Golem, but you would be unable to target it with say a Number C15: Gimmick Puppet Giant Hunter to destroy it and burn your opponent for 3000 damage. Retaliating "C" and Flying "C" are nuts, especially Flying "C" because there so many good playable Xyz Decks like Utopia, Exosister, and even K9 still. Retaliating is good against Fusion Decks if there are any floating around, and it can just hurt a lot of Decks in general by making cards be banished instead of going to the GY. I put Ultimate Slayer in the side because I ran out of points and Utlimate Slayer is 0 points, but I really just had available space in the Extra Deck that I needed to fill with something. So, I just chose to play Ultimate Slayer and targets to send in the Extra Deck. 

Is this a great Deck in Genesys? I think it's fine at the very least. It's just a really simple Deck to play that has a lot of available space for non-engine choices and that can also end on a good number of interruptions.

Regretably, the Familiar Possessed forms are not playable in this format. Actually, a lot of good generic spellcaster support came out way too late for this deck, but I did the best I could.

 

As for actually playing the deck, it's pretty standard stuff. There's a fair amount of hand sculpting since you'll need it and protection to ensure you'll get control of at least one card. That aside, Magician of Faith also plays a key role here, enabling the reuse of certain staples, which you'll definitely need to compensate for the low power of your monsters.

1.1 update 9/24/2025
Trying to maximize on Mirage, so I could see hand traps in the main as well. It maybe that the main deck needs something like the super polies to actually crack going second.

It's time to craft up a Genesys Deck, thanks to the new rules and point system! 

Taking my personal IRL Dinomorphia deck and melding it with some other archetypes that I love, find enjoyable, and mashing them together to see if they'd be worth while. 

1. Links and Pendulums are out, which means Soul of the Supreme King is out. 
2. Rexterm being as expensive as he is, is a perfect card for most play along with the amount of support offered. 
3. Kaiju's only got hit by Slumber, so otherwise pretty runnable across the board. 
4. Pots are in a nice abundance thanks to the point system. 
5. Lilith as a card searcher since Fossil Dig's too expensive to run with Rexterm within your allotted 100 points. 
6. Owner's Seal will allow the Xyz Dragons to run amock once you pop them off. 
7. No side deck as of yet, but will update as needed / when I play around with it more.

In a pinch you can also use Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous effect for Granguignol the Dusk Dragon send Diabellstar Vengeance for Syncho plays with Poplar of the White Forest into Snake-Eyes Vengeance Dragon . Ratios are a bit wack, will need to play around with the ratios more, might end with Arias the Labrynth Butler  not being a handrap anymore and less traps, but for now when it works, it's fun and it works!

deck_description: Shadow Wizard Enchantress Gang, we love discarding Dracoback
When Genesys got announced my mind immediately ran to Suship. After looking around a bit, I think I have a fun little recipe going on here.

First draft of a Centur-Ion list for Genesys after a few games with a less focused build. With the lesser power in the format we can afford to focus on the typically neglected Centur-Ion backrow and the free torrential which becomes one sided while Primera sits on the bench. I'm currently still debating Skull Meister's position in the main deck in favor of more board breakers or backrow since the format isn't too fast from inital tests.

Why the Enake-Eyes Spell+Extra Deck?: I found myself needing non-destruction removal and sending monsters to the backrooms was one way to lower my opponent's options without "removed from field" triggers even occuring. Some decks do punish this with their own Snake-Eyes Damned Dragon but this deck has ways to escape the backrow in engine. Enigmaster Packbit also stands out here as an additional option which does great work in our own backrow!

Hopefully this inspires other lists!

trying to make dracotail work since the deck already has that old-school low-to-the-ground feel in the TCG. microdosing coplium.

My first attempt at a Ghoti list for Genesys format. Not 100% sure about the non-engine yet, still trying to figure out what to run in this low hand-trap format. The engine should be solid, though. You can consider running Ixeep if you want to brick less on hands where you have the field spell and no normal summon, but I've found that you only run into that problem once in a blue moon, and you really don't want to draw Ixeep otherwise.

I'm always a Ghoti believer and I want to believe my fishy friends can be a real meta threat in this lower powered environment, but we'll see how the meta shakes out.

deck_excerpt: Witness the birth of myth and magic
I just really like these guys okay?
deck_description:
My entire thought process was:

  • Going second
  • Any level 2 + any Spright/Nimble Beaver/Deep Sea Diva/Rescue Cat
  • Make Gigantic
  • Gigantic get Blue
  • Blue get Jet
  • Jet get Gamma Burst
  • Win

Experimental build for genesys. Sky striker cards are nice for non effect monsters for the tenyi's but it's most likely not worth it cause they're a bad draw after you do anything. I wish there was a better way to reliably get non effects out for this deck but using the swordsoul tokens as the main source is prob the best way as you can have more room for other stuff. I replaced sthana with mapura cause I don't think sthana's second effect will do anything as the token can't be summoned back. I didn't know what to really put for side deck but I do like kurikara. Other than that, I hope I see more experimental deck profiles for swordsoul, hopefully someone cooks something crazy up.

IDK, I just think D-Maid can be a neat deck in Genesys Format. One approach could be ussing all your point in their engine, as 2 Sheou, 2 Lady's, and 2 Tidying are 100 points by themselves. But I think the better approach is just using the 60 points needed and use the remaining 40 in non-engine. In this version I'm ussing Super Poly as a great board breaker or disruption not many decks can play around in the format. If you don't go the same route you can still use the points in other good cards like the Charmies, Dragon Rulers, or even Dracotail. This is a more "Pure" approach, in what I call "Dragon Control".

The only part I don't fully trust is the side deck, I may need to see how the meta develops and change it based on that.

deck_excerpt: Six Samurai Genesys, new format, old friends :)
deck_description:
This relatively simple Six Samurai Deck is my first attempt at building for the Genesys format.

With Gateway of the Six being a 100 point card, including it is highly risky, and locks you out of the Synchro Shi Ens as boss monsters. Instead, we want to keep using the Shi En's alongside Enishi and Kizan. Legendary Six Samurai - Enishi is also featured in this variant, as he is still a super powerful Quick Effect bounce that can be special summoned with Asceticism of the Six Samurai. Playing without Smoke Signals hits the consistency of this deck a bit, as you gotta be more lucky drawing your starting pieces for your Extra Deck consistency Card which is Legendary Lord of the Six Samurai - Shi En. Your searches are primarily done by Kizaru who can be special summoned onto an empty field using Double Dai, to set up followup turns, for example by searching Legendary Six Samurai - Kageki, Anarchist Monk of the Six Samurai, Enishi or Secret Six Samurai Hatsume. Little Cameo appearnce of Hop Ear Squadron, with which you can utilize Kizaru to go into Legendary Lord of the Six Samurai - Kizan or Legendary Lord of the Six Samurai - Enishi during your opponents turn, with which you can interrupt them a little as well.

In testing, this deck makes for very exciting, anime-like duels with friends! Try it out if you can!
